  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 21:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " sq. The proper glory of the city is further described. It has no temple, because there is no need of one; for its temple is God himself and the Lamb. Nor does God, together with the Lamb, have a special dwelling-place in the city, but it is filled with the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δόξα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of God, everywhere present in it,[4352] and the city itself is indeed the bride of the Lamb[4353] who is immediately present to all the inhabitants of the city.[4354]",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They, therefore, need not the light of sun and moon; for[4355] the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δόξα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of God and the Lamb itself fill them with light.[4356] Here where, indeed, the description implies that the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δόξα τοῦ θεοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " corresponds to the sun, and that of the Lamb to the moon,[4357] it does not follow that the same distinction is made also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 21:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",[4358] because there it is only a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φωστήρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that is mentioned, viz., the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δόξα τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
